    "body": "## Problem\r\n\r\nSeparation markers (`%=`) are ignored within item groups. This lead to a regression in Neovim 0.12 due to the overloaded item group syntax to set the ruler width: the `%=` works in the ruler, but not when the ruler is incorporated into the statusline where the item group syntax is interpreted in the usual way (because the ruler is now included as an expression, rather than pre-rendered by the ruler code), see #39984.\r\n\r\nTruncation markers (`%<`) are not ignored within item groups, but only processed at the end outside of the group context, and only the first one actually has any effect. Meanwhile, item groups are always truncated from the left, regardless of included `%<`s. There is also a bug with `%<`s in hidden groups, see #39984. It would be more helpful if the truncation of each item group could be controlled separately.\r\n\r\n## Solution\r\n\r\nAllow %= in item groups (new feature). For example, the ruler expression in the default statusline `%-14.(%l,%c%V%)\\ %P` can now be written `%18(%l,%c%V%=\\ %P%)`, which actually works in both the statusline and the ruler, where it also sets the correct ruler width. It also becomes helpful when neither the left-aligned, nor the right-aligned part is of constant width, e.g. `%20(%l,%c%V%=\\ %P%m%)`.\r\n\r\nScope %< to item groups and make top-level and group truncation consistent (breaking change). Now, groups are by default truncated at the first item, and truncation can be controlled for each item group separately:\r\n```vim\r\nset stl=%.15(%<path:\\ %f%) \" <th/to/file.txt (previous default without %<)\r\nset stl=%.15(path:\\ %<%f%) \" path: <file.txt (new default without %<)\r\nset stl=%.15(path:\\ %f%<%) \" path: /path/to>\r\n```\r\n\r\nSome minor edge-case issues were fixed along the way. See commit messages.\r\n\r\nRemaining problem: I wanted to extend the tests from #21879. Unfortunately, they currently don't fail when the corresponding code is removed, at least not on my machine, and I don't know how to test this myself.\r\n\r\nFix #39984",
